                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"><span style="font-size: 16px; line-height: normal">As her eyes adjusted to the gloom of the swamp, Koori sighed softly and brushed away what seemed to be a horde of mosquitoes.  “Ah isn’t Innothule just lovely this time of year,” she mumbled to herself as she unfolded the map.  In the dim light she could make out where Grobb had once stood, now crossed off and marked as Gukta.  Koori had not been there since the web-footed ones had over taken it … and was not to anxious to visit now, except for a scroll she had found written by an elder enchanter named <a href="http://www.therunes.net/forums/viewtopic.php?t=284" target="_blank" class="postlink">Veledrara</a>.  She had written about an ancient spell that would give enchanters the power to guise themselves as a froglok, another parlor trick for the masses.
<br />

<br />
Walking through the swamp in a rapid pace, she made her way quickly to the town and moved around the guards that protected the young tadpoles.  “You dare to threaten the residents of Gukta? Your corpse will make a fine snack for the creatures of the swamp.”
<br />

<br />
Koori glanced behind her and saw the angry glare of the guards.  With a sigh and a shake of her head she dashed toward the front gate of town.  “You dare to test my strength? Your corpse will rot where it lies!” 
<br />

<br />
“You would think after almost 63 seasons I’d remember I was a Teir`Dal,” she grumbled to herself as she escaped to the safety of the Outpost of Marr.  The guards did not follow, sure that their comrades within would take care of her.  However, by the time she passed the first froglok guard inside the gate her ivory hair shimmered a brilliant red and her ebony skin was hidden beneath the illusions of a fair wood elf.  Pausing a moment she glanced around the city … her map looked like gibberish to her.
<br />

<br />
A small frog in a white robe approached her and bowed, a dubious look about him … Koori chanted softly and the frog blinked and smiled.  “Greetings, Lady Koori. I am Guide Kledoki, here as a guide for those who are lost to the various locations throughout the outpost. If you know the name of the spot you need to go, ask me to guide you there and I will help you there. If you would like a list of the places I can show you to, let me know and I shall give you that list.”
<br />

<br />
Koori knew the one she was looking for would be found near a certain vendor.  “Show me the wizard spell merchants, please.”
<br />

<br />
Guide Kledoki nodded. “Follow me, Lady Koori, I shall show you the way.”
<br />

<br />
As the froglok led her through the town they passed a sad looking troll in a cage. Basher Iglak said,  “Dis cell too small, much too small. Me needs to stretch da achin' bones. Promise be good if yous let me come out for dat.”
<br />

<br />
Dar Guard Rubog lets out an annoyed sigh, “Exactly how foolish do you believe I am, Iglak? How about I make you a deal. You can come out of your cell when snow and hail fall on the swamps of Innothule.”
<br />

<br />
Koori shook her head and sighed.  Trolls had never did her any harm … she pondered taking a moment to help the poor thing but decided against it, she was here for purpose and the basher didn’t look like he was in any immediate harm.  Just then a tadpole raced around her and attacked a wandering jungle hatchling, she cast a small haste spell on the youngster and got a smile in thanks.
<br />

<br />
Guide Kledoki said,  “We have arrived. This is where you will find the Wizard spell merchants.”
<br />

<br />
Koori looked around, in back in a cave spied an elder froglok.  She approached him and bowed slightly.  “Are you Master Scribe Uklo?”
<br />

<br />
Master Scribe Uklo nodded and smiled.  “Well met Lady Koori! Welcome to Gukta, the Outpost of Marr -- our new home and base of operations for our fight to remove the trolls from the rest of our beautiful swamp.  The liberation of Gukta was quite a battle!  Many brave Froglok warriors, a good dose of powerful magic and the blessings of Mithaniel Marr allowed us to cleanse this place of the vile Trolls.”
<br />

<br />
She could tell by the glint in his eye he wanted to share more information with her.  So she encouraged him.  “What powerful magic?” she inquired.
<br />

<br />
“Our battle wizards called many comets of ice from the sky, along with bolts of pure magical force, brutal walls of flame and even illusions to confuse and disorient the stupid trolls.”
<br />

<br />
“What illusions?”
<br />

<br />
“A select few of Mithaniel's chosen know the secrets of spinning illusions.  This skill allowed our bravest warriors to infiltrate the Troll's defenses and ensure victory.  These are some of our most closely guarded secrets.  We only teach them to a select few so they can better aid us in our battle.”
<br />

<br />
Koori tried not to seem too excited.  “Will you teach me?”
<br />

<br />
Master Scribe Uklo frowned.  “You must first prove yourself a friend of Gukta before I will teach you our secrets.”
<br />

<br />
“All right, how can I prove myself?'
<br />

<br />
“Very well, I will put your loyalty to the test.  Long ago, a great hero of our people lost his life fighting the Trolls. He was in Rathe Mountains investigating a rumor that the Trolls were stockpiling special weapons in an effort to turn the tide of war back in their favor. He was ambushed by a group of troll marauders and their captain Krignok.  He fought valiantly, slaying the marauders and eventually locking swords with the captain. But in the end, exhaustion got the better of him and he died by the troll's hand. The Krignok respected the froglok's ferocity and swore that they would one day finish their fight. So through a dark ritual the troll Captain locked the froglok's spirit in his own sword and broke it into 3 pieces. One piece he placed on the battlefield where they fought. The other piece he gave to an infamous troll warrior to guard. The location of the third piece has been lost over the time but there are clues as to where it may be.”
<br />

<br />
“And who is this infamous troll?”
<br />

<br />
“Gribnor is one of the strongest trolls alive, he is also one of the shortest. His strength is the reason that the Troll Captain entrusted him with a piece of the sword because he knew that it would be almost impossible for anyone to take it away from him. Last we heard Gribnor had taken up residence in Neriak Third Gate along with the rest of those vile trolls. I warn you to be careful as allies of Gukta are not welcome in the home of Innoruuk's children.”
<br />

<br />
“Where can I find more clues?” Koori asked.  The Scribe blinked at her with a confused look.  “What clues?” she asked again in simpler wording.
<br />

<br />
Master Scribe Uklo nodded with understanding.  “The troll captain spent some time in the lower part of Guk. Apparently he was trying to control the undead frogs there and use them against us. His plans did not see fruition and while trying to escape he dropped the sword blade. It is rumored that another explorer found it and the power drove him insane doomed to wander the halls of Lower Guk seeking only to destroy others. I believe you will find this to be the toughest piece to retrieve.”
<br />

<br />
“And where is this battlefield you speak of?” The scribe looked at her.  “What battlefield?  Where is the battlefield?”  She sighed softly and shrugged.  “I shall do as you ask old one and prove myself worthy of your teaching.”   She bowed and glanced around looking for the guide but he was gone.  “Great … lost again,” she mumbled.
<br />

<br />
A small hand tugged on her robe.  “Do you have anything to spare plz?”
<br />

<br />
Koori raised an eyebrow at the young beggar.  “I’m sorry I do not support beggars, go test your skills against the creatures of the swamp, in turn you will not only gather strength but loot items you can sell for money.”  The tadpole made a rude gesture at her and wandered off, looking for a more willing mark.
<br />

<br />
“Master, I think I'm starting to get the hang of this! I feint like so, and then counterattack with a lunge like SO. It's all coming together!”
<br />

<br />
“Yes, yes, fine work. You show promising form and style. Watch your balance, and keep your back foot firmly planted like this. Yes, good.”
<br />

<br />
Koori passed by the teacher and pupil hoping to find a familiar landmark.  
<br />

<br />
** Momma? ** The voice tickled her ears.
<br />

<br />
** Hello, lil one, sorry I did not wake you … was just running a quick errand in the lair of the froglok’s first. **
<br />

<br />
** It’s okay, Momma, coming to join you. **
<br />

<br />
** Good, I seem to be misplaced … again. **
<br />

<br />
The whispers stopped and Koori continued to wander the town, finally finding her way outside the outpost.   There she waited for her daughter, Meredith to join her.  Her wait was short and soon the two women were exchanging hugs.   The pair were an odd combo, one with skin as dark as ink and the other as fair as any wood elf could be … but that is a tale for another day.  
<br />

<br />
“So what did the old froggy tell you?”
<br />

<br />
“Seems our first stop is in the lair of the frogloks of old … Guk.”
<br />

<br />
”Oh fun … fun … caves of gloom and slime.  How deep do we have to go?”
<br />

<br />
“The piece I need was last seen within the lair of the undead … the live frogs have no qualms with me … do they still dislike you?”
<br />

<br />
“They would like to see me on the menu as ‘Druidess Legs’” Meredith said with a grin.
<br />

<br />
The two women made their way through Innothule Swamp, sped along by the powerful magic of the Druidess.  Once within the dank caverns Meredith concealed herself and the twosome had an uneventful walk to the depths of Guk.  Once they passed through to the deeper parts of the caverns, Koori took the lead, lulling the few alive frogs left and then making them both invisible to undead frogloks.  
<br />

<br />
“I’ve heard rumors of a crazy gnome within these caverns … the froglok spoke the power of the blade may drive one insane.  Can you sense anything lil one?”
<br />

<br />
Meredith paused a moment … “I do sense something deeper, Momma … a gnome for sure … but he seems corrupted.”
<br />

<br />
The two ladies moved deeper following the path Meredith’s druid powers gave her.  Suddenly the floor disappeared beneath them and they tumbled down into a pit.  There they found a Beastlord and warder locked in battle with a gnome and its pet.
<br />

<br />
Meredith kept an eye on the Beastlord’s health as they tried to stay out of the battle.  The gnome fell before the might of the Beastlord and a ghoulish figure rose from the gnome’s corpse.
<br />

<br />
“May I speak to the spirit?” Koori asked.  
<br />

<br />
The Beastlord named Hibasi nodded.  “Tis all yours, was not a battle I wish to start, but I did finish it.”
<br />

<br />
“Hail, a spectral shimmer”
<br />

<br />
“Thank you for releasing me, take this and find the rest if you truly wish to help me.”  The spectral shimmer faded away.
<br />

<br />
Koori glanced down at the sword blade that appeared in her hands.  “Let us continue, Lil One, our next stop is Rathe Mountains … can you bring us to the bog the ogres call home?”
<br />

<br />
Meredith nodded and whispering an ancient druid spell the both of them vanished only to appear moments later in the marshlands called Feerrott.  With Meredith playing the role of guide, they moved quickly to the mountains of Rathe.  Once within the valley the pair paused.  “Okay now what Momma?”
<br />

<br />
“I’m not really sure I could not get the old frog to speak of the battlefield …”
<br />

<br />
“Momma, I sense something dead this way … something powerful …”
<br />

<br />
“Lead on, Lil One … could not hurt to check it out.”
<br />

<br />
Led by the power of Meredith’s goddess the two made their way to some crumbling ruins, the Druidess stopped in front of one such ruin; in the corner was a crumbled skeleton.  Koori could tell it had once been a froglok by the webbing on its fingers.
<br />

<br />
Kneeling and looking at the ground in respect she whispered, “I wish to recover what is lost”
<br />

<br />
A spectral energy surrounded Koori as something appeared before her, in her hand a tarnished pommel appeared.  “One step closer, now we must venture into the depths of Neriak and seek out a tiny troll named Gibnor.”
<br />

<br />
“Fun, fun, fun … why don’t we go shake King Thex’s hand while we’re at it?” Meredith said with a playful smile.  “Lavastorm coming up, Momma.”
<br />

<br />
*~*~*~*~*~*~*~*~*~*~*~*~*~*~*~*~*~*~*
<br />

<br />
Neriak was not a good place for either of them to be as they snuck through the streets, hidden from view.  Meredith for obvious reason … Koori’s alliance with the Koada`Dal had been discovered but as far as she knew it was only known to the warriors of Neriak.  Most other’s still treated her as a normal Neriak citizen … even warmly if the dark ones were capable of such emotions.
<br />

<br />
Gathering information from various merchants they were able to find the strong hold of Gribnor the Small.  Hidden in the shadows Koori crept inside, out on the balcony she found the smallest troll she had ever seen, on either side stood two powerful looking thugs.  “I believe we’ll need help for this part.”
<br />

<br />
She called out to the guild and alliance … most seem too busy or not too anxious to rush into the depths of Neriak.  However, Sharrazade, a powerful minstrel within the guild quickly signed up and crept her way to join them in the depths of Neriak’s Third Gate.
<br />

<br />
As time passed on her daughter’s eyes been to close on their own.  “I’m afraid I have to go, Momma … I’m sorry but if I don’t slumber … I’ll be no good to anyone.”
<br />

<br />
“It’s okay Lil One, have sweet dreams … I think I shall have to call on the powers of my beloved for this fight.”  After her daughter was safely back in the Plane of Knowledge, Sharrazade used a mask and took the form of a Teir`Dal … to pass time the two ladies made playful passes at a young guard on patrol.
<br />

<br />
After awhile Tenakakhan heard their mischievous pleas for help and snuck into town to aid them.   As the time passed the threesome started to seriously consider trying the small one on their own when Koori got a whisper from Arbo, a powerful grandmaster … he and Mediclare, a cleric, were coming to aid them.  That would surely be enough … though a second whisper told her that her husband and friends were also coming to help.
<br />

<br />
Soon a party of eight stood ready … Bonwirn, an outrider from the guild Seventh Cavalry, Arbo the grandmaster of the Seventh, Mediclare who also shared the Seventh banner and Koori’s beloved Seaotter the Arcanist the final Seventh member.  With them stood Tenakakhan the warder ally from Legacy of the Companions, Sharrazade the Minstrel from her own guild and the powerful Templar Palidoc, also from Silver Phoenix Alliance.
<br />

<br />
A few buffs were cast but Koori had grown impatient and nudge Arbo.  “Go have fun!”  The monk winked at her and ran into the tower.  A few moments later they watched the guards on the balcony give a shout and chase after him, as well as the one they stalked.  
<br />

<br />
She heard Arbo mumble in the bond they shared as group … “Damn I hit the caster …”
<br />

<br />
Out the front gate ran the monk on his heels was Gribnor the Small shouting, “U come to laugh at da tiny Troll, I show u why dat not nice to do!”  His guards fooled into returning to their posts.  However, the dark elf named Evin X`Lottl with the shuriken still in his leg was not so easily fooled.
<br />

<br />
Using her power to tash the small troll she turned her attention to the enraged dark elf.  “Your will is now mine, brother!”  She commanded and mind became her puppet.  “Attack the small troll my pet!”
<br />

<br />
She chuckled softly as the castor turned his magic against his ally.  The laughter died in her throat as her husband cursed.  “He has a lot more life then I thought …” His powerful mana burn had hurt the troll but not to the extent they had hoped.
<br />

<br />
The battle raged and under the might of their foe Arbo fell.  “'Who be da laugher now, I may be da tiny Troll but I bash big!”
<br />

<br />
“Hang in there … we can do this!”
<br />

<br />
Bonwirn was the next to fall … and the troll turn his attention to Tenakakhan that had been firing arrows at him with the force of the most powerful sword blows.  Koori frowned, if Tena fell the only other melee would be Sharrazade.  “Damn it, Die!” She swore.  And on command the small troll did just that.  Somewhere she got the feeling, something was a bit happier with her for killing the midget.  From his remains a ghost appeared.
<br />

<br />
“Hail, a spectral shimmer”
<br />

<br />
“Take this final piece and hurry, my power gets weaker by the moment.'” The spectral shimmer faded away
<br />

<br />
Koori’s fingers wrapped around Tarnish Cross Guard.  
<br />

<br />
“Now where do we go?” Sharrazade asked with a grin.
<br />

<br />
“And what was that for?” Bonwirn asked as he collected the last belonging from his still warm corpse.
<br />

<br />
“I must return these pieces of an ancient sword to an old froglok … then perhaps that will be proof enough and he’ll grant me the power to become like him.
<br />

<br />
Her beloved rolled his eyes … “Oh great now you get to turn into a slimy frog … I didn’t think you even LIKED frogloks.”
<br />

<br />
“I don’t really care for them but there is a blank in my spell book that must be filled.”
<br />

<br />
“Yeah right beside true north … okay my kitten but for now let’s rest you can do the remainder of this foolish quest in the morning.”
<br />

<br />

<br />
To Be Continued …
<br />

<br />

<br />
Big Thanks To:
<br />

<br />
Meredith, Bonwirn, Seaotter, Palidoc, Arbo, Sharrazade, Tenakakhan, and Mediclare for their aid so far in this quest.</span></span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=543790" target="_blank" class="postlink"><img src="http://www.geocities.com/jeremy_moffitt/images/everquest/jksig2.gif" border="0" /></a></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
